":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"au","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Maine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Main  .","French: topographic name from Old French <i>maine</i> ‘dwelling, residence, abode’, or a habitational name from any of numerous places so named."],"variants":[{"name":"Main","meanings":["Scottish: from a shortened form of the Scandinavian personal name   Magnus  , which in Older Scots became <i>Manus</i> and <i>Mane</i>.","English (of Norman origin) and French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ma(g)ino</i>, <i>Meino</i>, from <i>magan</i> ‘strength, might’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname for a large man, from Old French <i>magne</i>, <i>maine</i> ‘great, big’."]}]},{"name":"Alixe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alixe De Beaumont au Maine was born in 1169, in Beaumont-sur-Oise, Pontoise, Val-d'Oise, Île-de-France, France as the daughter of Lucie De L’Aigle. She had at least 2 daughters with Gauthier De Gisors. She died in 1224, in Gisors, Eure, Normandy, France, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1169–1224":"1169–1224","1146–1207":"1146–1207","1193–1252":"1193–1252","1201–1257":"1201–1257","1151–1247":"1151–1247","1247":"1247","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","1252":"1252","1151":"1151","1193":"1193","1207":"1207","Gisors, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Gisors, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Beaumont sur Oise, France":"Beaumont-sur-Oise, Pontoise, Val-d'Oise, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Gisors, Eure, Normandie, France":"Gisors, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1169–1224":"1169–1224","1146–1207":"1146–1207","1193–1252":"1193–1252","1201–1257":"1201–1257","1151–1247":"1151–1247","1247":"1247","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","1252":"1252","1151":"1151","1193":"1193","1207":"1207","Gisors, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Gisors, Eure, Normandie, Ranska","Beaumont sur Oise, France":"Beaumont-sur-Oise, Pontoise, Val-d'Oise, Île-de-France, Ranska","Gisors, Eure, Normandie, France":"Gisors, Eure, Normandie, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1169–1224":"1169–1224","1146–1207":"1146–1207","1193–1252":"1193–1252","1201–1257":"1201–1257","1151–1247":"1151–1247","1247":"1247","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","1252":"1252","11